# ðŸ† Find Second Largest Element in an Array (C++)

This repository contains an efficient solution to find the **second largest element** in a given array without sorting it.  

The solution works in **O(n) time complexity** and does **not modify the original array**.

---

## ðŸ“Œ Problem Statement

Given an array `arr[]`, return the **second largest distinct element**.  
If no such element exists (e.g., all elements are equal), return **-1**.

### Example:

| Input | Output |
|--------|--------|
| `[12, 35, 1, 10, 34, 1]` | `34` |
| `[10, 10]` | `-1` |
| `[5, 4, 3, 2, 1]` | `4` |

---

## ðŸš€ Approach

We maintain two variables:

- `largest` â†’ Tracks the biggest value found so far  
- `secondLargest` â†’ Tracks the second biggest distinct value

We **scan the array only once** and update these values based on comparisons:

1. If current value > `largest` â†’ update both `largest` and `secondLargest`
2. Else if value is between `secondLargest` and `largest` â†’ update `secondLargest`

---

## ðŸ§  Time & Space Complexity

| Factor | Value |
|--------|-------|
| **Time Complexity** | `O(n)` |
| **Space Complexity** | `O(1)` |
| **Stable Solution** | âœ” Yes |
| **Handles Duplicates** | âœ” Yes |

---

## ðŸ“Œ C++ Code Implementation

```cpp
class Solution {
public:
    int getSecondLargest(vector<int> &arr) {
        int largest = -1, secondlargest = -1;

        for(int i = 0; i < arr.size(); i++) {

            // If new element is greater than the current largest
            if(arr[i] > largest) {
                secondlargest = largest;
                largest = arr[i];
            }
            // If element is smaller than largest but greater than second largest
            else if(arr[i] > secondlargest && arr[i] != largest) {
                secondlargest = arr[i];
            }
        }

        return secondlargest;
    }
};
